      <div xml:id="NA10-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu uṭaṉpōkkun tōḻi kaiyaṭuttatu (ET: kaiyaṭaippaṭuttatu).</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is [how] the confidante takes refuge in [their] eloping.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA10">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            aṇṇān tēntiya vaṉamulai taḷariṉum</l>
<l>            poṉṉēr mēṉi maṇiyiṟ ṟāḻnta</l>
<l>            naṉṉeṭuṅ kūnta ṉaraiyoṭu muṭippiṉu</l>
<l>            nītta lōmpumati pūkkē ḻūra</l>
<l>            viṉkaṭuṅ kaḷḷi ṉiḻaiyaṇi neṭuntērk </l>
<l>            koṟṟac cōḻar koṅkarp paṇīiyar</l>
<l>            veṇkōṭ ṭiyāṉaip pōor kiḻavōṉ</l>
<l>            paḻaiyaṉ vēlvāyt taṉṉaniṉ</l>
<l>            piḻaiyā naṉmoḻi tēṟiya vivaṭkē.</l>

        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        <l>Even when [her] beautiful breasts, looking upwards [and] eminent, slacken</l>
        <l rend="indent">on her<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ivaṭkē</term>: here we certainly have to read a kind of circular construction, and since it cannot be connected with <term xml:lang="ta">nīttal</term> (which takes a direct object), it is best to take it with the concessive construction, literally: "if the breasts should slacken to her".</note>, who has come to believe in your unfailing good words,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">like in the success of the spear of Paḻaiyaṉ,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">lord of Pōor with white-tusked elephants,</l>
        <l rend="indent3">when the Koṅkars were humbled by the victorious Cōḻars</l>
        <l rend="indent3">with jewel-adorned long chariots [and] sweet strong toddy,</l>
        <l>[and] when [she] ties, because of whiteness, [her] good long tresses<note place="foot">Cf. KT 23.2 for the whiteness of hair as a sign of age.</note></l>
        <l rend="indent">which hang down without jewels on [her] gold-like body</l>
        <l>– beware of leaving [her], o man from a village rich in flowers.</l>
    </lg>
